item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: exlover
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:
Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)
...or something like this:
The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.
As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

wp:postmeta.wp:meta_value:
As you go through this course you will begin to develop a solid plan to regain your confidence and get your ex back. If he/she loved you once, he can love you again.
This isn't an overnight solution. Analyzing yourself and what has changed or what went wrong will be critical. Additionally, there may be behaviors that you have embraced that... over time... have become a hindrance to romance or keeping it together.
The initial stages of a relationship up until two years can be considered the honeymoon phase. All seems well during that time. The honeymoon phase can last from six months to two years.
After the honeymoon phase, one or both members of the relationship can get disillusioned. That's because the emotional thrill diminishes. At that point often relationships will either end, or one of you will discover new ways to enliven your connection.
So, how do you make a new start after you have known someone for a while. That is the question that leaves couples at a dead end. And, you may or may not like the solutions; but, they are universally successful at reviving the dwindling romance. They can also be used to get your ex back.

If you and your ex are talking and you both want to find a way to work it out, then you can try some of the following suggestions. If your ex is not willing and has jumped ship already, you will need to study the course and develop a plan.
Special date nite once a week. Sounds obvious or even a waste of time; but, it isn't. Couples who set aside one night a week to do something fun are often able to revive the relationship.
At least one romantic night each week. If you have gotten to the point in your relationship where there is no more romance and/or intimacy, you can hang it up. You gotta make time for it every week.

No TV during the day time unless you are watching it together. The exception to that is... if he loves sports. You watch some sports with him and then he watches something with you. In theory, it is best to leave the tube off until 5:00 in the evening. Television can be a form of avoiding the elephant in the room. If one party doesn't want to talk about the relationship, they will often get into the habit of turning on the television to avoid conversation.
Keep consistent and same sleeping hours. Sleeping hours are from 9:00 p.m. through 6:00 a.m.
Both parties have daytime activities. There is no couch/TV watching during the day. If one person doesn't have a job, then they can garden, volunteer
Good relationships that last take attention and time. They don't just happen accidentally. It is so worth it to have a great relationship that is close, romantic and intimate. Take the time to invest in your relationship. Watch it flourish.

That's right. Obsession is relationship suicide.
Don't get obssessed. You must control this all-too common response to being "dumped!" Obsession will turn off your ex-lover faster than almost anything. It communicates a sense of neediness that no one likes. And BTW, no one can fulfill that neediness because it arises from a sense of personal self-loathing.
A better response is to do anything and everything to stay calm, get help, get some counselling so that you can calm down before you do something you will later regret when you return to your right mind again. Yes, that's right... when you are obssessed you are not in your right mind. You are in a state of fear and panic. It is the last thing you want to demonstrate to your ex-lover.
Be clear, when you get obsessed, you are a different person. And, not an attractive one either.
Obsession leads to stress and impulsive behavior.

The solution: understand your being obsessive. If you don't know, ask your family and friends. If your ex states that you are obsessed believe him or her. Give yourself and your ex some time and space. Seek help from others, not your ex lover.
You both need time to heal and consider the future with a level head and honest goals. You may find that you were not mean to be together.
If you are certain you are right for each other, allow your ex some breathing room. Nothing stimulates a romance more than being apart and/or thinking that the other has moved on with someone else.

Even though you don't want to do anything but cry and scream in the beginning, try to force yourself to go out with friends and to date a little if you can. You must trust this process. Dating someone else is extremely helpful to getting over your obsession with someone else. It sends a psychic message to everyone that you are going to be ok and can live without your ex lover.
Be strict with yourself and take this advice. Study this course and be systematic about your approach to either getting your ex-lover back or moving on to something even better.

Sometimes, when someone breaks your heart, the shock, disappointment and loss cause a behavioral shift. Instead of feeling confident, the injured party can become defensive, mean, hateful or even pathetic. Avoiding falling into this trap is going to be one of the first things necessary to get yourself back in the running.
It's critical that you understand yourself and separate the facts from your own interpretation (or meaning) that you place on the situation. Yes, you have been dumped; but it usually doesn't mean what you think it means. It is so critical at this juncture to collect yourself and avoid falling into deep depression or self-loathing. You have work to do and it's going to take a clear head.
As human beings we apply meaning to the things that come at us from the outside world. Once you decide on a "meaning" of a certain situation, your mind will cause you to behave in ways that support that meaning.

Ask yourself... what does it mean that he/she dumped me. Does it mean "I'm not good enough"? Does it mean "he/she met someone else?" And if so, "am I just nothing?" "don't my feelings count?" And, "if I was good enough six months ago, why am I not good enough today?"
Notice that instead of just feelings those things, you are analyzing them and writing them down--taking note of them.
Did you know that you can change your mind about the meaning of anything. The "fact" and the "meaning" of the fact are separate. You can have one "fact" and endless "meanings" placed on a fact by various people who experience the same "fact" but have different meanings for the fact.

Here's what this looks like:
Someone has broken your heart. Yes, it is sad. You thought you would be together forever. Maybe you thought you heard wedding bells. But, now he (or she) is off with someone else and has gone who-knows-where. Those are the facts. Right now you have no control over those facts. What you can control is your response and your interpretation (the meaning).
Meaning. Instead of falling apart, you stop and decide what your meaning is. It can be anything; but, to serve our purpose here... which is to get your "ex" back... The meaning would be someting like this...
We have had a temporary set-back in our relationship. I am willing to take a step back and let him (her) breathe for a while. I haven't changed. I am still my loveable self, so it is something different (or even wrong) with him/her. It could be that she is busy. It could be that she feels like she has no options. It could be that she (he) is listening to a friend or relative giving advice. My decision is to place the following meaning: She has been tired lately. I will let her rest and be free for a few weeks. I am ok. I feel good about myself. I have a great personality and I am good for her/him. I have tools. I have this resource to give me the tools I need to attract my lover back to me.
There are endless resources here that will give yo the tools you need to get your ex back.
Keep reading!

The reason it is important to analyze the meaning you place on a breakup is that your interpretation of the "meaning" will change your experience of it and it will magically ripple beyond you to have an effect on anyone else involved.
